                    <msContents>
                        <summary>
                            <seg type="para">This fragment is a bifolium of a manuscript containing 
                                the <title>Letters of Libanius</title>, a Late Antique orator and teacher of rhetoric, probably copied during the 14th century.
                                The bifolium was acquired by Constantin von Tischendorf (1815-1874) during travels in the East, 
                                from <bibl subtype="external" type="MS">
                                    <ref target="https://www.loc.gov/item/00271076757-ms">Sinai, Monastery of St. Catherine, Cod. gr. 1198</ref>
                        </bibl>.
                                This bifolium was originally between ff. 111v and 112r. Thirty-three more leaves from the same manuscript
                                were donated by Tischendorf to the University Library of Leipzig, and 
                                today make up 
                                <bibl subtype="external" type="MS">
                           <ref target="https://digital.ub.uni-leipzig.de/mirador/index.php#055ffbcf-9e25-4730-b871-e8089e9a621d">
                                    Leipzig, Universitätsbibliothek Leipzig, Cod. gr. 38 (Tischendorf 7)</ref>
                        </bibl>.</seg>
                            <seg type="para">Dr Matteo Di Franco</seg>
                        </summary>

                        <textLang mainLang="grc">Greek</textLang>

                        <msItem n="1">
                            <locus from="1r" to="2v">ff. 1r-2v</locus>
                            <author key="person_v17225859" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/17225859">
                                Libanius, 314-393 CE
                            </author>
                            <title type="desc" xml:lang="eng">Letters (fragment)</title>
                            <incipit defective="true">
                        <locus from="1r" to="1r">f. 1r</locus>
                                ἐνθυμοῦ πόσοι παρὸν ἐν πόλει διατρίβειν, τοὺς ἀγροὺς αἱροῦνται</incipit>
                            <explicit defective="true">
                        <locus from="2v" to="2v">f. 2v</locus>
                                καὶ παρ’ ἐμοῦ τοῖς γράμμασιν ἔπαινον οὐκ ἐψεύσατο· ἐκρότουν γὰρ</explicit>
                            <note>Letters 1508 (defective at the beginning), 1517, 1518, 1524, 1526, 1527, 1533, 1536, 1540 (defective at the end) Foester. 
                                The selction of Libanius' letters in the Sinai manuscript was arranged in six group of one hundred each:
                                the letters are numbered in left-hand margings as [ξβʹ] ξγʹ-οʹ and 
                                the number of the <hi rend="italic">centuria</hi> is written in Greek numerals, in red ink, 
                                on the upper margin of each recto folio: ͵ρ ϛ (<hi rend="italic">centuria sexta</hi>)</note>
                            <note>TLG 2200.001</note>
                        </msItem>
                    </msContents>

                    <physDesc> 
