                                    </seg>
                                </extent>

                                <foliation>The bifolium is foliated with the numbers 1-2, in Arabic
                                    numerals, in pencil, recto, upper right.</foliation>

                                <collation>
                                    <signatures type="leaf">
                                        A reverse folio count in black ink on the lower margin of each verso folio, 
                                        repeated on the opposite recto folio, serves as a signature in Arabic letters, 
                                        consistent with the use of Arabic numerals and letters in the origin manuscript
                                        (cf. the <ref target="http://www.manuscripta-mediaevalia.de/dokumente/html/obj31586198">
                                            Leipzig manuscript description</ref>):
                                        f. 1r ف, f. 1v-2r غ, f. 2v ع.
                                        </signatures>
                                </collation>

                                <condition>There are water and brown stains on the bifolium. 
                                    The fragment is now sewn into a white paper cover.</condition>
                            </supportDesc>

                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout columns="1" writtenLines="36"> One column of 36 lines.
                                    <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                                        <height quantity="165">165</height>
                                        <width quantity="110">110</width>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>

                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote scope="sole" xml:id="hand-1">
                                <p>The text was copied in a scholarly, small-format <term type="script">mixed minuscule</term> 
                                    script, in dark brown ink. Accents are small and modestly executed, 
                                    ascenders and descenders are restrained, and there is limited use of abbreviations.</p>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>

                        <decoDesc>
                            <decoNote type="decInit">Each letter begins with an ornamented initial,
                                outlined in red ink.</decoNote>
                        </decoDesc>

                        <additions>
                            A modern hand has added the numbers of the letters
                            in pencil according to <ref target="https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_rNte5JRY8T0C/page/n4/mode/2up">
                                Joannes C. Wolfius' edition (Amsterdam 1738)</ref>.</additions>
                        
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding calendar="gregorian" when="2019">
                                <p> The fragment has a modern card binding reinforced with cloth
                                    inside the spine.</p>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>

                    <history>
                        <origin>The style of script suggests that the manuscript from which this
                            fragment came was copied in the <origDate calendar="gregorian" notAfter="1350" notBefore="1300">first half of the 14th century</origDate>.</origin>

                        <provenance>
                            The fragment was part of the manuscript Cod. gr. 1198 owned by the 
                            <placeName key="place_g1100137" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/1100137">
                                Monastery of St Catherine on Mount Sinai</placeName>. 
                            The fragment was in the possession of the Biblical scholar 
                            <name key="person_v56713311" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/56713311" role="fmo" type="person">
                                <persName type="display">Constantin von Tischendorf (1815-1874)</persName>
                                <persName type="standard">Tischendorf, Constantin von, 1815-1874</persName>
                     </name>.
                        </provenance>

                        <acquisition calendar="gregorian" when="1876">Bought by the University
                            Library from Tischendorf's executors in 1876.</acquisition>
                    </history>

